
[1]enfilade

   ENFILA'DE, n. [L. filum.] A line or straight passage; or the situation
   of a place which may be seen or scoured with shot all the length of a
   line, or in the direction of a line.

   ENFILA'DE, v.t. [from the noun.] To pierce, scour or rake with shot, in
   the direction of a line, or through the whole length of a line.

   In conducting approaches at a siege, care should be taken that the
   trenches be not enfiladed.

   In a position to enfilade the works at Fort Isle.
